✅ PART 1 — JPA (Java Persistence API)
✅ What is JPA?

✔ JPA is a specification, NOT a framework
✔ Defines rules for ORM (Object Relational Mapping)
✔ Provides interfaces & annotations
✔ Needs an implementation (Hibernate, EclipseLink…)

Think:

JPA = Contract / Guidelines
Hibernate = Implementation / Engine

✅ Why JPA Exists?

Without JPA:

❌ Vendor lock-in (Hibernate APIs everywhere)

With JPA:

✔ Write standard annotations
✔ Switch providers easily

✅ Core JPA Annotations
✅ 1. @Entity

Marks class as DB table.

@Entity
public class Employee {
}

✅ 2. @Table

Optional table name mapping.

@Entity
@Table(name = "employees")
public class Employee {
}

✅ 3. @Id & @GeneratedValue

Primary key definition.

@Id
@GeneratedValue
private Long id;


Strategies:

✔ AUTO
✔ IDENTITY
✔ SEQUENCE
✔ TABLE

✅ 4. @Column

Column customization.

@Column(name = "emp_name", nullable = false)
private String name;

✅ JPA Entity Example (Complete)
@Entity
@Table(name = "employees")
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    @Column(nullable = false)
    private String name;

    private double salary;

    // getters & setters
}

✅ Entity Lifecycle States (VERY IMPORTANT)

Interviewers LOVE this.

✔ Transient → New object, not in DB
✔ Persistent → Managed by EntityManager
✔ Detached → Exists but not tracked
✔ Removed → Scheduled for deletion

✅ EntityManager (Core JPA Interface)

Used to interact with persistence context.

Common methods:

✔ persist() → insert
✔ merge() → update
✔ remove() → delete
✔ find() → fetch

Example:

entityManager.persist(emp);


In Spring Boot → handled internally.

✅ Relationships in JPA (CRITICAL)
✅ ManyToOne (Most Common)
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "dept_id")
private Department department;


✔ Foreign key stored here
✔ Default fetch = EAGER

✅ OneToMany
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "department")
private List<Employee> employees;


✔ mappedBy → owning side defined elsewhere
✔ Default fetch = LAZY

✅ OneToOne
@OneToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "passport_id")
private Passport passport;

✅ ManyToMany
@ManyToMany
@JoinTable(
    name = "student_courses",
    joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
    inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
)
private List<Course> courses;

✅ Fetch Types (Favourite Question)

✔ LAZY → Load on demand
✔ EAGER → Load immediately

Performance critical.

✅ Cascading (VERY IMPORTANT)

Controls child entity operations.

Types:

✔ PERSIST
✔ MERGE
✔ REMOVE
✔ ALL

Example:

@OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)

✅ JPQL (Java Persistence Query Language)

✔ Works on entities, not tables

SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary > 50000


NOT:

SELECT * FROM employees ❌

✅ PART 2 — Hibernate (Deep Dive)
✅ What is Hibernate?

✔ ORM Framework
✔ Implements JPA specification
✔ Handles DB interaction
✔ Adds extra features

✅ What Hibernate Actually Does

Converts:

Java Object ↔ Table Row


You work with objects → Hibernate generates SQL.

✅ Hibernate Core Features
✅ 1. Automatic SQL Generation
repo.save(emp);


Hibernate runs INSERT.

✅ 2. Dirty Checking (VERY IMPORTANT)

Hibernate auto-detects changes.

emp.setSalary(70000);


No explicit update needed.

✅ 3. First-Level Cache

✔ Session-scoped
✔ Prevents duplicate queries

✅ 4. Lazy Loading Mechanism

Hibernate loads associations when accessed.

✅ 5. HQL (Hibernate Query Language)

Similar to JPQL.

FROM Employee WHERE salary > 50000

✅ 6. Pagination Support
query.setFirstResult(0);
query.setMaxResults(10);

✅ 7. Dialect System

✔ DB independent
✔ PostgreSQL / MySQL / Oracle supported

✅ Hibernate Relationship Example
@Entity
public class Department {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Employee> employees;
}

✅ N+1 Query Problem (CRITICAL)

Occurs when:

✔ Parent query executed once
✔ Child query executed per row

Fix:

✔ JOIN FETCH
✔ EntityGraph

✅ JOIN FETCH Example
@Query("SELECT d FROM Department d JOIN FETCH d.employees")
List<Department> findAllWithEmployees();

✅ Advantages of Hibernate

✔ No manual JDBC
✔ Auto SQL
✔ Caching
✔ Lazy loading
✔ DB portability
✔ Transaction support

✅ PART 3 — JPA vs Hibernate (Interview Favourite)
JPA	Hibernate
Specification	Implementation
Standard APIs	Concrete engine
Portable	Vendor specific features
Needs provider	Provider itself
✅ PART 4 — MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS 🔥
✅ Why use JPA if Hibernate exists?

JPA provides standardization & portability.

✅ What is Dirty Checking?

Hibernate auto-syncs object state with DB.

✅ Lazy vs Eager?

Lazy improves performance by deferring loads.

✅ Entity States?

Transient / Persistent / Detached / Removed.

✅ JPQL vs SQL?

JPQL → Entities
SQL → Tables

✅ What causes N+1?

Improper lazy loading strategy.